turns: Hillary Clinton's security detail in Iowa included a second Scooby van, mechanically identical to her usual Chevy conversion van, for added protection. The Secret Service employ decoy vehicles to add confusion to VIP travel plans. The two Scooby vans arrived separately and left together in a seven-car motorcade. The Iowa motorcade also included four black Suburbans and a white minivan. The Secret Service often deploys duplicates of aircraft and cars used to transport VIPs.

A mother of six in Georgia has been left without a home and all her possessions after a fire destroyed her rented condo. Kalimah Dixon said she was lucky to escape the blaze with her children, aged one to 14, but is finding it difficult to find a permanent home while being unemployed. Dixon, who was renting the condo for the last four years, quit her job to enroll in school full time to complete her degree in business management. She has started a GoFundMe page to raise money for a new home and has so far raised $4,619 in donations.

An Australian couple who entered into a surrogacy arrangement in India were told that the boy born through the arrangement would be left stateless if they abandoned him, according to new documents obtained by ABC. The couple had planned to take only their daughter back to Australia, leaving the boy behind with friends in India. The documents show that Australian government officials were aware of the situation. The Indian government does not recognize surrogate children as citizens. There were concerns that the boy may have been sold, and if money had been exchanged, it would be considered trafficking. The case is similar to the recent baby Gammy case.

Kecil, a one-year-old orangutan, was rejected by his natural mother and two surrogate mothers before being placed with Maggie, a 53-year-old orangutan at Chicago's Brookfield Zoo. Maggie has raised four of her own children and one surrogate, and has proven to be an excellent mother to Kecil as well. The pair have formed an inseparable bond, and Kecil is set to make his first public appearance this weekend. The zookeepers are hopeful that Kecil will learn from Maggie how to be an orangutan, as she has already taught him how to groom and play.

Javier Pastore, star player for Paris Saint-Germain, has declined Eric Cantona's assertion that he is the best footballer in the world. Pastore believes that Lionel Messi and Cristiano Ronaldo are superior players. Pastore has been praised by Cantona for his creativity and assists. Pastore and PSG will play against Barcelona in the second leg of their Champions League match on Tuesday, with a 3-1 deficit to overcome to advance to the semi-finals.

Amanda Burleigh, a midwife at Leeds Teaching Hospitals NHS Trust, has successfully fought a decade-long battle to give mothers more time attached to their newborns before the umbilical cord is cut. She believed that clamping the cord within seconds of delivery was wrong and harmful to the baby. Burleigh and a group of medical professionals amassed evidence that stopping the blood flow so early could be harmful, particularly raising the risk of iron deficiency anaemia. They have finally succeeded in getting the National Institute for Health and Care Excellence (NICE) to change its guidelines, stating that doctors and midwives should not routinely clamp the cord earlier than one minute from the birth of the baby. The change means mothers get the chance to hold their babies for a moment while still connected to them. Burleigh overcame persistent doubts from colleagues and Dr David Hutchon, a retired obstetrician, supported her. However, there was resistance to change and some doctors still believe that immediate clamping reduces the risk of mothers haemorrhaging. The practice of immediate cord-clamping may be harmful for premature babies.

French President Francois Hollande has vowed to "show no mercy" if French peacekeepers in the Central African Republic are found guilty of raping hungry children in exchange for food. The French defence ministry has denied covering up a scandal involving allegations that six children, including four who say they were direct victims, were sexually abused by the soldiers at a displaced person's camp. Fourteen soldiers have been accused and the abuse is alleged to have taken place between December 2013 and June 2014. An investigation was launched when the ministry received a leaked UN report on the subject in July last year. A French soldier taking part in 'Operation Sangaris' stands guard at the Boali church.

A Texas pastor's wife, Aracely Meza, has been arrested for injuring a child by omission after attempting to resurrect a two-year-old boy at a church in Balch Springs. Meza was caught on camera using oils and praying in an attempt to bring the child back to life. The boy, identified by a witness as Benjamin, is said to have been possessed by demons according to pastors. Meza and her husband, Pastor Daniel Meza, presided over the church services held at the residence which also operated as a church. The residence was not registered to operate as a church, and the body of the child was taken to Mexico the following day after his death. An investigation is underway involving both state and federal authorities.

John Higgins and Graeme Dott led the charge for Scotland in the first round of the Betfred World Championship, with Higgins winning 10-5 over Robert Milkins and Dott winning 10-8 over Ricky Walden. Higgins is looking to win his fifth world title and is feeling confident after beating Milkins, while Dott is a proven Crucible class act and is hoping to make a deep run in the tournament. Stephen Hendry is the only player ahead of Higgins in terms of number of world titles won.

Barcelona won over Celta Vigo in La Liga with a 1-0 victory, thanks to Jeremy Mathieu's winning goal. Neymar, Dani Alves, and Adriano played key roles in the win. After the game, the Brazilians were seen in matching denim, taking to Instagram to celebrate their victory. Dani Alves, who is being linked with a move away from Barcelona, also shared a photo of the trio on social media. Jeremy Mathieu admitted that Barca had a tough time and struggled to keep the momentum going after the international break. He praised his defensive partner, Gerard Pique, for his impressive performance against a difficult opponent.

Jose Mourinho is reportedly planning to sign Atletico Madrid midfielder Koke this summer, and is considering offering second-choice left-back Filipe Luis to Atletico as a makeweight in the deal. Koke's release clause is reported to be around £50million, but Chelsea could be willing to pay this to add to their tired-looking midfield. Chelsea's technical director Michael Emenalo recently travelled to Spain to watch Koke in action, and he was instrumental in Atletico's run to the Champions League final last season.

Tom Ballard, the son of a renowned climber who died while attempting to summit K2, plans to climb the mountain himself 20 years after her death. He has already completed the first solo ascent of all six great north faces of the Alps in a single winter season and is now training for K2. His mother, Alison Hargreaves, was only the second person to climb Everest without sherpas or bottled oxygen, and her death on K2 at the age of 33 became a tragic milestone in climbing history.

A consortium of companies has claimed that there could be up to 100bn barrels of oil worth trillions of pounds located in the Weald Basin, an area spanning Surrey, Sussex, Hampshire and Kent in southern England. UK Oil and Gas Investments, which has a 30% stake, discovered the potential at a site five miles from Gatwick airport during test drilling. They say the oilfield holds 158m barrels per square mile, equating to 100bn barrels across the basin. However, industry experts remain sceptical of the claim and warn that only a fraction of the Weald Basin oil may be accessible for extraction.

The British Veterinary Association has withdrawn its support for the shooting of free-running badgers in controversial pilot culls. The organization now suggests that trapping badgers in cages and then shooting them would be a more effective and humane approach to culling badgers in Somerset and Gloucestershire. The BVA still supports badger culling as a means to tackle tuberculosis in cattle. However, animal welfare campaigners criticized the BVA's stance on cage-trapping and shooting, calling it "regrettable." Liz Truss, the Environment Secretary, has promised to roll out more culls across the country if the Conservative Party wins the upcoming election. She urged politicians not to make the controversial cull a party political issue and criticized Labour for pledging to give up on culling. The government's strategy includes cattle movement controls, vaccination in "edge" areas around disease hotspots, and culling where the disease is rife.

It is argued that modern technology has made our lives more complicated and can cause pitfalls in relationships. Examples of these pitfalls include constantly checking smartphones and social media during a date, taking photos of food, changing relationship status too quickly on Facebook, and texting too much after the date. To avoid these common mistakes, Blu e-cigarettes have suggested leaving phones off the dining table, not taking food photos for Instagram, not checking in on location apps, not updating relationship status on Facebook immediately, avoiding texting too much after the date, keeping a taxi app handy, using Snapchat to update friends, not bragging about Tinder matches, not assuming date will find everything funny, and not using Google Glass to record the date.

Tottenham are without Kyle Walker and Hugo Lloris due to injury, while Jan Vertonghen is a doubt for their match against Aston Villa this weekend. Aston Villa boss Tim Sherwood is again set to be without a key trio, with Alan Hutton (ankle), Ashley Westwood and Scott Sinclair (both hamstring) among the players set to miss out. The match is set to kick off at 3pm on Saturday, with Lee Probert as the referee. Tottenham are favourites to win, with odds of 4/7, while Aston Villa are 5/1 and the draw is 14/5. Tottenham have won their last five Premier League meetings with Aston Villa and Tottenham's White Hart Lane stadium has seen the most first half goals this season.

A mother in Australia made the difficult decision to give birth to her baby girl at just 20 weeks due to a serious form of Spina Bifida. The baby, Annabelle, was born weighing only 290 grams and lived for just five minutes before passing away. The mother contacted Angel Gowns, a not-for-profit organisation that redesigns donated wedding dresses into outfits for babies who pass away too soon. Angel Gowns created a beautiful gown for Annabelle to be buried in and also gave the family a replica dress to keep in their home. The family was able to spend time with Annabelle dressed in the gown before she was buried, and the mother looks at the replica dress every day to remember her daughter. Angel Gowns currently donates outfits to over 80 hospitals and funeral homes across Australia and also deals directly with families. To donate or volunteer, visit [www.angelgownprogram.com.au](http://www.angelgownprogram.com.au).

A black police constable named Ronnie Lungu has won a race discrimination case against Wiltshire Police. The employment tribunal ruled that the Zimbabwe-born officer was unlawfully discriminated against on grounds of race after the force did not promote him due to the color of his skin. The panel found that Mr. Lungu's internal assessments were specifically downgraded in order to make him appear unworthy of promotion, and that senior staff made negative comments about him based on his race. The force has been ordered to take steps to address any failings and reassure Mr. Lungu that any complaint of discrimination will be taken seriously. The Chief Constable has expressed his concern and the force will appeal the judgment.
A parent taught their newborn baby to suck on a plastic water bottle and filmed the process, which has received over 190,000 views on YouTube. Many commenters found it cute and adorable.

A set of rare and valuable photographs taken in the 1850s have surfaced and are set to be auctioned off tomorrow. The images, captured by photographer Hugh Owen, showcase some of the first ever photographs of the city of Bristol and could fetch up to £30,000. The pictures depict the city centre, waterfront, St Mary Redcliffe church, and buildings such as The Fourteen Stars Tavern, which was pulled down in 1857. The albumen prints were made in the 1870s from the original paper negatives of the early 1850s. Some of the buildings pictured have changed dramatically since the 19th century, but others, such as St John's Gate at the Church of St John the Baptist, have hardly changed at all. The set of pictures provides a fascinating glimpse into Bristol's past, showcasing its historic architecture and landmarks.

Pro-Ukip businessman Harvey Boulter is trying to defeat two Tory candidates, Tom Tugendhat in Tonbridge and West Malling, Kent and another candidate in Somerset, in a vendetta against Liam Fox. Boulter gave £30,000 to the Ukip candidate fighting Fox in Somerset and will spend another £30,000 to defeat Tugendhat. Boulter was outraged by the court case where he was sued for libellous remarks by Fox and his friend Adam Werritty. Tory Party declined to comment.

A six-year-old Aston Villa fan named Charlie Pye applied for the job of manager after Paul Lambert was sacked. Although he missed out on the position to Tim Sherwood, Sherwood wrote Charlie a letter congratulating him on his credentials and his "very capable backroom staff". Sherwood also mentioned that the club would like to keep the letter on file "just in case". Charlie was appointed captain of his local team, Norton Lindsey, and received a special message from Sherwood about being a captain. Charlie was delighted to receive the letter from Sherwood and it meant a lot to him.

Atletico Madrid defeated Cordoba 2-0 in their La Liga match, thanks to goals from Antoine Griezmann and Saul Niguez, to move above Valencia into third place. Valencia have 60 points and can reclaim third spot with a win against Villarreal on Sunday, while Atletico are four points behind second-placed Real Madrid, who have 64 points, and three clear of Sevilla in fifth. Griezmann's goal came in the fifth minute and Saul's goal secured the victory and placed Atletico ahead of Valencia.

An 18-year-old mother-of-one from Castle Donington, UK died after taking M-Cat at a house party. Abby Swinfield was rushed to the hospital after the party but died a week later due to multiple organ failure caused by two heart attacks. Her family believes her drink was spiked and is calling for an investigation into the party. One person has been arrested on suspicion of supplying drugs.

A playground in Tokyo has been found to have dangerously high levels of radiation, raising concerns for the safety of children in the area. Soil underneath a slide at the park showed radiation readings of up to 480 microsieverts per hour, nearly double the recommended annual limit of exposure for a person. The source of the radiation is currently unknown, but authorities believe it may be coming from something buried underneath the park. The playground has been fenced off, and the city has set up a health advice office to answer concerns from parents. Japan has heightened concern over radiation following the 2011 Fukushima disaster.

Amir Khan believes that Kell Brook called him out for a payday, as Brook has only faced one decent opponent in his career and is not a big name beyond Sheffield. Khan has denied a fight with Chris Algieri next month, claiming that there are "some more options on the table." Khan insists that he is not avoiding Brook, and that he will make a lot of money in the sport regardless of whether he fights Brook. The Bolton-born boxer has reiterated his intention to take on Brook within the next 12 months, although he claims that Brook only wants the fight because of the money it will earn him.

A Dallas architect, Matt Mooney, has transformed 14 shipping containers into a stunning modern three-bedroom home, called "PV14". The home boasts a 40ft long swimming pool on the ground floor, a 1,400 sq ft roof deck, and a 360-degree view of White Rock Lake and downtown Dallas. The home features exposed ceilings and unpainted shipping container gates as doors. The designers wanted people to know what they were standing in when they stepped into the home. Gooden said the house's walls are made of sheet rock, which would make the home look 'normal' if the ceilings weren't left exposed. The house's upstairs levels are outfitted with maple wood floors to complement the views of the nearby park and lake. Mooney knew he wanted to build a home out of shipping containers 25 years ago, and after more than two years of design and construction, the couple are finally preparing to move into their new home.

Jordan Ibe is close to signing a new five-year contract with Liverpool, keeping him at Anfield until 2020. He has made a notable impact in his eight appearances since returning from a loan spell at Derby County. Liverpool is also expected to announce new contracts for Jordan Henderson and Martin Skrtel this week. Contract talks are ongoing with young defender Jon Flanagan as well. Liverpool has also agreed a new three-year shirt sponsorship deal with Standard Chartered worth around £30million a year.

Rik Mayall's estate, worth £1.2 million, will be divided according to British government intestacy rules after the comedian failed to leave a valid will. Mayall's children will inherit a share of the net estate, resulting in a potential inheritance tax bill if the amount exceeds the threshold. Andrew Kidd, a solicitor, said that Mayall's widow would receive £250,000 plus all the chattels, while Mayall's children would receive half the remaining value of the estate. Mayall's personal belongings, including cars and furniture, would go to his wife, with the remaining half subject to inheritance tax if it exceeds the threshold. Kidd suggests that Mayall's family could avoid the tax by drawing up a deed of variation to split up the estate. Meanwhile, Mayall was instrumental in David Cameron's election as MP for Witney, despite being a committed Labour supporter. He recommended Cameron to the local Conservative Association in 2001, and they selected him for the seat.

The article describes the evacuation of Indian nationals and other foreigners from Yemen during a brief window when Saudi planes are not bombing the city. Air India has been flying people to Djibouti, a small African nation, and some evacuees have been leaving on boats from port cities such as Aden. The shelling and lack of electricity have made life in Yemen very difficult and many people are leaving behind much more than just their luggage. A professor who lived in Sanaa for 34 years said that he never felt like a foreigner but was exhausted and jangled by the shelling and lack of electricity. The Houthi rebels control Sanaa and the Saudi air force gave Air India a four-hour window to go to and from Sanaa and a specific travel route for a safe landing. From Djibouti, the evacuees will most likely disperse to their home nations.

An Italian priest has been sacked after claims emerged that he took part in gay orgies with a Swiss Guard. The priest was dismissed from his position in Taranto after an online lover contacted church authorities with a dossier containing evidence of the alleged activities, which included sexual role-play scenarios and explicit gay web chats. The labourer, who was seeking spiritual support from the priest, claimed that the priest tried to seduce him and organised orgies with priests and a Swiss Guard, although church authorities have not confirmed anyone else was involved. The Swiss Guard serves as the de facto military of Vatican City. The diocese of Taranto confirmed the priest's removal from pastoral care but denied any involvement of other priests.

A new study in the Journal of the American Medical Association (JAMA) has found no link between the MMR vaccine and autism, even among children with older siblings with autism. The study, which analyzed data from about 95,000 young people, found that vaccination had no effect on autism risk, whether or not a sibling in the family was diagnosed with autism. The study's lead author, Anjali Jain, said "Consistent with studies in other populations, we observed no association between MMR vaccination and increased ASD risk among privately insured children." The study also found that children with an older sibling with autism were less likely to get vaccinated, with vaccination rates of 86% for children with older siblings with autism, compared to 92% for children with unaffected siblings. The study's findings are consistent with previous studies over the last 15 years, which have ruled out a link between the MMR vaccine and autism.

A new report by Human Rights Watch has detailed the systematic rape, sexual slavery, and forced marriage of Yazidi women and children by ISIS fighters in Syria and Iraq. The organization has collected accounts from 20 women and girls who managed to escape their captors, which it says shows a pattern of organized rape and sexual assault. Yazidi women and girls were separated from their families, forced to convert to Islam, and repeatedly raped by ISIS fighters, according to the report. Some attempted suicide to avoid rape and need better medical and psychological support. The report has been published amid United Nations investigators finding evidence that ISIS is committing genocide against the Yazidi minority in Iraq.

A man named Kenneth Stancil, who is a former student of Wayne Community College in Goldsboro, North Carolina, allegedly opened fire in the campus library on Monday morning, killing one person and injuring several others. The 20-year-old suspect, who did not graduate from the college, is described as white, approximately 5'11", with a goatee and a tattoo over his left eye. Stancil is considered dangerous and is being searched for by police. The shooting occured around 8 am and law enforcement officials arrived at the scene within minutes. A lockdown was initiated, and students and staff were evacuated from the buildings. No further information has been released yet.

The new chief executive of Rotherham council may be paid up to £40,000 more than the outgoing boss due to "negative publicity" from the grooming scandal. The council has raised the salary offered to candidates to £200,000 from the previous £160,000. The rest of the cabinet resigned in February after a Government report said the council was "not fit for purpose" and "in denial" about exploitation. The council's HR chief said additional incentives may be necessary and a councillor is uncomfortable with the idea.

Cesc Fabregas will wear a protective face mask for Chelsea after breaking his nose during their match against Stoke City. The mask was made by the Ortholabsport in Milan and branded with Fabregas' initial and squad number. The center has worked with several football clubs and teams, including Chelsea, Manchester City, and the Italian national team. Fabregas traveled to Milan to have the mask fitted on Tuesday and could be ready to play against Queens Park Rangers on Sunday if selected by manager Jose Mourinho. Diego Costa is expected to miss at least two weeks of action with hamstring trouble.

Andros Townsend's wonder strike for England silenced his critics, including Paul Merson, and gave him motivation to perform well against Italy. Despite a topsy-turvy season, Townsend has kept faith from manager Roy Hodgson, who was rewarded with Townsend's exceptional goal in a 1-1 draw with Italy. Townsend celebrated with his Tottenham Hotspur team-mates.

A man named Joseph O'Riordan is on trial for attempting to murder his cheating wife, Amanda, who was left with life-threatening injuries after he stabbed her eight times with a kitchen knife. The attack occurred after O'Riordan discovered his wife's affair with a postman. O'Riordan wrote a letter to his wife from prison while on remand, asking her to gather some of his belongings for his trial. Amanda sobbed in court, saying she never wanted to hurt her husband and that all of this is her fault because she had an affair. In a police interview, Amanda described her husband as "passionate" and "vocally volatile" but said he had never laid a finger on her before. O'Riordan has pleaded not guilty to the charge of attempted murder.

The UK will open its first three proton beam therapy centres, to be operated by Proton Partners International, after cancer-stricken five-year-old Ashya King made a miracle recovery after receiving the treatment. The treatment centres will be located in Cardiff, London and Northumberland and will be available to NHS cancer patients by 2017, with the first in Cardiff expected to be operational by next year. The announcement comes after Ashya was given the "all-clear" following proton beam therapy at a centre in Prague. The group behind the new centres has committed almost £100 million equity finance, with renowned cancer and healthcare experts joining the team. The only proton beam facility currently in operation in the UK delivers "low energy" therapy for rare cancers around the eye. The NHS currently pays for those deemed appropriate for proton beam therapy to go to the United States for treatment, with around 400 patients having been sent abroad since 2008. The UK Government has announced that it will create two NHS proton beam therapy units which will open in 2018.

Ambulance bosses are recruiting paramedics from Australia because it is more cost-effective than training them in Britain. The London Ambulance Service has hired 400 paramedics from Australia and New Zealand in the last year, with the selection process taking place at five-star hotels. The flight and hotel expenses total £90,000 per trip, but the ambulance service has been able to hire an average of 200 paramedics, who are offered a £30,200 salary including London weighting. Many British paramedics are quitting due to frustration with overcrowded A&E units and an increase in non-urgent calls, and some are moving to advanced practitioner roles in A&E, GP surgeries, and call centres. The exodus has left the London Ambulance Service with 340 vacant posts out of a total workforce need of around 1,700.

Chelsea have partnered with fitness technology provider Technogym to equip their training ground with the latest state-of-the-art equipment to help players stay in top form. The club is currently seven points clear at the top of the Premier League standings with a game in hand and seven games remaining, and players including Eden Hazard and Nemanja Matic have been pictured training hard. Chelsea's assistant first team fitness coach and gym manager Carlos Lalin has hailed the club's partnership with Technogym, stating that it will help the team achieve even more success in the future. Technogym's founder and President Nerio Alessandri also expressed his pride in being selected as Chelsea's fitness equipment partner.

It is reported that scientists have discovered that babies are capable of understanding complex social situations and the laws of physics at a very young age. At only 11 months old, babies have already mastered the fundamentals of physics. In a study, babies were fascinated by magic tricks such as a ball appearing to pass through a solid wall, and they demonstrated this by repeatedly dropping the ball on the floor. The babies also reacted with surprise when a toy car appeared to defy gravity and float in thin air. The study also confirmed that babies are capable of understanding what constitutes bullying, friendship, and being a bystander, and they can comprehend these concepts at the age of just 13 months old.

Manny Pacquiao is training for his fight against Floyd Mayweather by running on the trails at Griffith Park in Los Angeles. He is swapping the gym for the great outdoors to work on his fitness and stamina. Pacquiao was joined by several fitness fanatics and his dog Pacman during his run. He showed off his skills by shadow boxing in front of interested spectators and worked on his core strength during a training session on the mats. Pacquiao revealed the multicolored mouth guard he will wear during the fight and confirmed his confidence with the container it comes in that reads 'MouthGuards for Champions.'

A cat named Biso was trapped behind a wall in a Cairo train station for five years and survived thanks to an elderly man named Uncle Abdo who fed him scraps of food every day. Biso was freed thanks to a social media campaign and animal rights activists. After his rescue, Biso ran away before anyone was able to catch him.

At least 35 workers were killed and the factory was set ablaze in an airstrike on a dairy factory in Yemen's Hodeida. The factory was being used as a rebel weapons cache, according to military officials. The airstrikes were part of a campaign by the Saudi-led coalition against Houthi rebels in Yemen. Scores of Yemeni expatriates in Tehran protested against the airstrikes, burning photos of Saudi King Salman and denouncing the Saudi Arabia-led alliance as an Iranian proxy.

A truck crashed on an elevated highway over subway and rail tracks in Boston's Dorchester neighborhood, causing delays for hundreds of morning commuters. Both drivers were taken to the hospital with non-life-threatening injuries. The collision caused headaches for locals trying to get to work, and replacement shuttle buses were run for southbound commuters. The truck was towed by crane at around 8:30am, but traffic remained backed up in both directions. No names have been released and state troopers are still investigating the incident.

Saracens Director of Rugby Mark McCall praised his young players after their latest European defeat and declared that the club has no intention of overspending in the competitive post-World Cup transfer market. McCall watched his side, which included five English-qualified forwards in the starting pack, battle in vain before losing 13-9 to Clermont on Saturday. The club's chairman Nigel Wray raised expectations they could be set to land a 'marquee' player from outside the league whose wages would sit outside next season's £5.5m cap. However, McCall said that the club is waiting for the right person to improve their side and not jump in to get a name just because of the post-World Cup availability.

The decomposing bodies of the men accused of killing 148 people in a Kenyan university attack were paraded in a primary school for the public to view. Survivor Cynthia Cheroitich, who hid in a wardrobe for two days, was rescued and taken to the hospital for observation. The authorities hoped that the public viewing of the bodies would help identify the attackers, who were all killed in the attack. Al-Shabaab has warned of more attacks on Kenyan cities and has vowed to make the country a "pool of blood".

Arsenal must make a decision on Petr Cech quickly or risk losing him to competition from other clubs, such as Liverpool, Paris Saint-Germain, Roma, and Inter Milan. Chelsea will demand at least £10m for the goalkeeper, who is entering the final year of his contract, but Cech will be a valuable acquisition given his status as a world-class goalkeeper in his prime. However, Chelsea may be reluctant to sell to a Premier League rival, and Arsenal may also face obstacles in negotiating a fee with the club. Cech is open to the idea of moving to the Emirates Stadium but ultimately the decision lies with Chelsea.

Frankie Dettori will not be riding horses under Sheik Joaan Al Thani's Al Shaqab banner in France this summer as the Sheik has signed up Gregory Benoist to ride those horses. The only exception is for Sheik Joaan's dual Arc winner Treve, who will continue to be ridden by Thierry Jarnet. Dettori will be focusing on the British flat season instead. The recruitment of Benoist is not seen as a snub to Dettori, but rather a result of Sheik Joaan's expansion of his operation, which now has more than 150 horses in Britain and France.

Lois Lilienstein, co-star of the Canadian preschool show "Sharon, Lois & Bram's Elephant Show" that aired on Nickelodeon in the 1990s, has died at age 78. She passed away from a rare form of cancer discovered last October. Lilienstein was born in Chicago and moved to Toronto in 1996. She joined Sharon Hampson and Bram Morrison in 1978 to form the singing trio Sharon, Lois & Bram. Their show "Sharon, Lois & Bram's Elephant Show" ran from 1984 to 1989 in Canada and continued in reruns on Nickelodeon until 1995. The show is best known for songs like "Skinnamarink" and "Peanut Butter." Lilienstein left the trio in 2000. Sally Catto, general manager of programming at CBC Television, paid tribute to Lilienstein for her contribution to Canadian kids' TV.

French freediver Guillaume Néry jumped without scuba gear into the world's second deepest underwater sink hole, Dean's Blue Hole in the Bahamas. He held his breath for several minutes while swimming back to the surface. The footage was filmed in 2010 by his girlfriend and fellow freediver, Julie Gautier.

A suicide bomber in Afghanistan blew himself up in front of the Kabul Bank in Jalalabad, killing at least 33 people and injuring more than 100 others. The ISIS terrorist group claimed responsibility for the attack, with the attacker named as Abu Mohammad belonging to their ranks and targeting government workers collecting their pay at the bank.

Laura Wells, a plus-size model, has launched a new swimwear line in collaboration with Swimsuits For All's trend range, SwimSexy. The collection is made entirely of 100 percent recycled material and is inspired by the ocean with coral reef scenes featuring throughout. The swimsuits are available in sizes 10 to 24 and come in one and two-piece designs with zippers, criss-cross straps, plunging V-necklines and high-waisted bottoms. The line was created to provide eco-friendly, fashion-forward options for curvy girls. The primary challenge in creating the collection was finding environmentally-friendly materials that were also affordable.

TrackYourDose is a new app developed by Germany-based firm esooka that records and keeps track of a user's personal radiation exposure, including exposure from medical examinations, changes in location, and flights. The app uses a mathematical model developed by scientists and meteorologists from the Physikalisch-Technische Bundesanstalt (PTB) in Germany and the University Oulu, Finland. By entering the details of their flights, users can calculate their radiation exposure from cosmic radiation on flights, as well as gamma radiation and cosmic radiation on the ground from medical examinations and other sources. The app aims to help users understand their exposure to radiation and make informed decisions about their health.

Blue Bell Ice Cream has suspended operations at an Oklahoma production facility due to a foodborne illness linked to the deaths of three people. The US Centers for Disease Control and Prevention recommends that consumers and retailers not eat or sell any Blue Bell brand products made at the company's Oklahoma facility. The recalled products were traced to a production line at the company's headquarters in Brenham, Texas. Blue Bell announced that it will conduct a thorough examination of the Oklahoma plant to determine the exact cause of the contamination and will resume operations once the investigation is complete.

Jon Hamm, best known for his role in Mad Men, has been exposed for his alleged involvement in a hazing scandal at the University of Texas at Austin in 1990. Court documents reveal that Hamm and other members of the Sigma Nu fraternity allegedly beat a prospective pledge with a paddle, lifted him by his genitals, and set him on fire. The incident left the pledge with serious injuries, and the fraternity was shut down after the alleged assault was reported to the police. Hamm was charged with hazing and assault, but the charges were eventually dismissed in 1995.

The UK government pledged to protect the Falklands from “Argentinian bullying” after Argentina launched legal action against British companies exploring for oil off the islands. This follows a speech by Argentine President Cristina Fernandez de Kirchner, which prompted the UK Foreign Office to summon the Argentine ambassador. Argentina accused three British and two US companies of working without permission to explore for oil in the islands' waters. The UK Foreign Secretary Philip Hammond said that President Fernandez de Kirchner’s threats against those who do business with the Falkland Islands were “illegal” and that the UK would protect the islanders from “Argentine bullying” as they develop their oil and gas industry. The UK Defence Secretary Michael Fallon last month announced plans to boost the UK's military defences of the Falkland Islands, and the Argentine president and ambassador publicly attacked the UK Government's plan to boost defences on the South Atlantic islands.

Passengers on board a Delta Air Lines flight from Tampa, Florida to New York City experienced some anxious moments when their plane landed at LaGuardia Airport and was met by firefighters wearing full protective suits. The crew reported an odor of smoke and firefighters used a thermal imaging camera to locate a potential heat source on board the plane. Passengers were kept on the plane for about 45 minutes and were eventually able to deboard normally. The cause of the odor was not immediately known. The plane was taken out of service for an inspection and any necessary maintenance.

David Luiz, the Brazilian defender for Paris Saint-Germain, has suffered a torn hamstring and will be out for at least four weeks. To alleviate boredom while recovering, he has debuted a new hairstyle, sporting a man bun. His teammates find the new look amusing, but the injury is a concern for the club as they aim for Ligue 1 and Champions League glory this season and Luiz will miss important matches, including the quarter-final against Barcelona.

US President Barack Obama has stated that diplomacy is the best way to deal with Iran's contested nuclear program, two days after the conclusion of a framework agreement with Tehran. He believes that a comprehensive, long-term deal is the best option, with rigorous inspections in place to ensure that Iran will be held accountable if it cheats. The final deal has yet to be reached, but Obama has hailed the agreement struck after tortuous negotiations in Lausanne, Switzerland, as a “historic understanding”.

A 12-year-old girl named Rose McGrath, who has been battling Leukemia for two years, has been kicked out of her private Catholic school, St. Joseph's Middle School, for low attendance and poor academic performance. The school claims that they made many accommodations for Rose but none of them helped her enough. Rose's mother, Barbara McGrath, said that the school's actions are seriously failing their child, who is still recovering from her illness. The family has filed a complaint with the Office of Civil Rights and is waiting for a response. Rose has lots of support from family and friends but she will need to find another school if she is not allowed back at St. Joseph's.

Passive smoking affects plants, causing them to take up nicotine from contaminated soil and plumes of smoke, according to a study by Dirk Selmar and colleagues at the Technical University of Braunschweig, Germany. The findings, published in Springer’s journal Agronomy for Sustainable Development, suggest that the widespread occurrence of nicotine in medicinal, spice and food plants may, at least in part, be due to other nicotine sources apart from the illegal use of insecticides. The study also shows that the concentration of nicotine in plants decreases over time as it is taken up by the roots and processed in the leaves. The findings shed light on the hitherto unexplained success behind farming practices such as crop rotation and the co-cultivation of certain vegetables.

A video captured two male chameleons fighting for a female mate in Madagascar. The more aggressive chameleon chased the other out of the tree and along a concrete wall, snapping at each other and struggling to keep their footing. The aggressor gained the upper hand and took a huge bite out of his rival, who squirmed in pain. The video ends as the defeated chameleon crawls away and the victorious one gives chase. The battle was referred to as "bataille du chameleons" by the video maker.

Jack Cosgrove, a 20-year-old prop from Worcester Warriors, has signed a two-year deal with Edinburgh Rugby, tying him to the Murrayfield club until 2017. Cosgrove has represented Scotland at the Under 20 level and has been cited by teammates such as Damien Hoyland and Magnus Bradbury as a strong set-piece player with a bright future. He looks to add to Edinburgh's squad and learn from fellow prop Alasdair Dickinson, and will join the club as they continue to build from their recent European Cup Final appearance.

Aaron Hernandez, the former New England Patriots football player who was convicted of murder and sentenced to life in prison without parole, has been moved to the maximum-security Souza-Baranowski Correctional Center near Shirley, Massachusetts. He is being held separately from other prisoners and is on suicide watch. Hernandez was known to have used "angel dust," a drug that causes users to experience hallucinations and violent outbursts, for at least a year before the murder of Odin Lloyd.

Manchester City's young Academy players are not yet ready to step into the first-team squad and the club is looking to invest in homegrown talent, which makes Jason Denayer, who is currently on loan at Celtic, an attractive prospect for next season. Celtic is keen to retain Denayer's services, but faces an uphill struggle to do so. Manager Manuel Pellegrini has confirmed that the club will be required to invest heavily in 'homegrown' talent this summer. The current Premier League regulations require clubs to carry a minimum of eight homegrown players, and Denayer, who is from Belgium but falls into this category, would fit the bill. A number of young City professionals, including PSV's Karim Rekik and Marcos Lopes with Lille, are on loan and may be brought back to plug some of the holes next season.

Ander Herrera revealed in a short Q&A video that he wears both his forename and surname on the back of his shirt for superstitious reasons, following a successful spell at Athletic Bilbao. He hopes to carry on his good form with Manchester United and has admitted to being an emotional player. Herrera scored twice as United beat Aston Villa in the Premier League on Saturday and celebrated with a lot of emotion. The midfielder is looking forward to more emotional moments in the future as United target silverware.

Despite suffering a 6-1 defeat at the hands of Bayern Munich in the Champions League quarter-final, Porto supporters gave their team a hero's welcome upon their return to Portugal. Fans chanted and hugged the players, recognizing the team's achievement in reaching the quarter-finals for the first time since the 2008-09 season. Porto coach Julen Lopetegui admitted they were defeated by a superior Bayern team, but he was proud of his side's performance in the tournament.

The BBC has come under criticism for creating an online computer game that simulates the difficult journey Syrian refugees face as they try to escape their war-torn country and enter Europe. The game, called "Syrian Journey," allows players to choose a character and make decisions about whether to flee by land or sea, with often grim outcomes such as being beaten and hurled into the Mediterranean, being sold to militia, or being separated from family. The BBC has defended the game as a way to show the difficult choices refugees face and has received over a million hits online.

Boston Marathon bomber Dzhokhar Tsarnaev has received another plea for mercy as his victims, Jessica Kensky and Patrick Downes, who lost limbs in the attack, have called for him to be sentenced to life in prison without parole instead of the death penalty. They argue that their position is emotional and practical. The Richards, who lost their son Martin in the blast, have also called for Tsarnaev to receive the same sentence, stating that continued pursuit of the death penalty would prolong reliving the most painful day of their lives. Moments before the attack, Martin and Tsarnaev were photographed together at the finish line. Tsarnaev's legal team has been trying to paint him as a secondary player in the plot orchestrated by his older brother Tamerlan, who died after a shootout with police. Massachusetts outlaws the death penalty, but it is still a sentencing option in Tsarnaev's federal trial.

Hamdi Ulukaya, the CEO and founder of Chobani, has settled a lawsuit filed by his ex-wife Ayse Giray, who claimed to be entitled to half of the $2 billion Greek yogurt empire. The settlement came just before a ruling was due on whether Giray could be named a shareholder in Chobani's predecessor company, Euphrates. The two were married for only two years in the 1990s, and the lawsuit was initially filed in 2012 for a 53% stake in the company. Chobani is currently considering replacing Ulukaya as CEO due to a product recall in 2013 that led to a $87 million negative EBITDA in the fourth quarter. The recall was caused by bad design and layout at the $450 million Idaho factory, among other issues.

Diego Costa has suffered a setback in his recovery from a hamstring injury, limping off 11 minutes after coming on as a substitute for Chelsea in their win against Stoke City. He has been told he will miss just over two weeks, but is expected to return in time for Chelsea's crucial clash against Arsenal. Costa will focus on strength sessions and intensive massages in the injured muscle, and will see a specialist before stepping up his rehabilitation. He will definitely miss Chelsea's games against Queens Park Rangers and Manchester United, but could make a return against Arsenal on April 26. Mourinho may decide to use the striker sparingly for the run-in depending on how close the title race is. Loic Remy is likely to lead the line in Chelsea's next game against QPR.

The England C team, which has been in operation for 36 years, is facing the axe as part of the Football Association's spending review. The team, which plays only a few games a season, has been identified as a potential area of saving as FA chairman Greg Dyke looks to fund his masterplan for grassroots football, including the construction of more 3G pitches in urban coaching hubs. Former Barnet boss Paul Fairclough is the current manager of the team, which includes non-league players aged 23 and under, and has included players who have gone on to represent Scotland, Wales and even England, although not for the senior team. However, with no fixtures planned since a meeting last week, concerns have increased about the long-term future of the team.

James Haskell, the London Wasps captain, dressed up as Iron Man, a character played by Robert Downey Jr. in the new Avengers: Age of Ultron movie, in a serious-looking Instagram post. The highly-anticipated movie premiered at Westfield London shopping centre on Tuesday evening, with fans queuing up to see the A-list cast. Haskell returned to the club where he started his career for the 2012 season, and has since become a big part of the England squad with 57 caps to-date.

Police are urging witnesses of a middle-aged woman's tirade towards a Muslim woman on a Sydney train to come forward after video of the incident was published by Daily Mail Australia. Stacey Eden, 23, stood up for the Muslim couple and recorded the incident, in which the woman made racist and Islamophobic comments. The police spokeswoman contacted Daily Mail Australia and encouraged witnesses to come forward. Ms Eden's recording shows her fuming at the woman's comments and defending the couple. The incident ended with the ranter telling Ms Eden to "breathe." The Muslim couple thanked Ms Eden for her stand. The Islamophobia Register Australia praised Ms Eden's actions.

Ursula Ward, the mother of a man killed by Aaron Hernandez, is suing the former NFL player and will call him to testify in the wrongful death suit. Hernandez was convicted of killing Odin Lloyd in 2013 and is already serving a life sentence without the possibility of parole. Ward's lawyer said she wanted to look Hernandez in the eye and ask him why he killed her son. The lawsuit, filed in December 2013, was put on hold during the criminal trial and will now resume so Ward's lawyers can seek damages. Hernandez's former team, the New England Patriots, have already agreed to dismiss any money owed to him and will not pay him any further compensation.

Britain has struck oil in the Falklands, which could be worth billions of pounds, and heightens tensions with Argentina over ownership of the islands. The Argentine minister has said they will prosecute oil companies operating off the Falklands coast, claiming they are acting illegally in Argentine territory. Argentina has a long-standing claim to the Falklands, which is known as the Malvinas. Lord West, a former First Sea Lord, believes the oil discovery will lead to further Argentine claims over the territory in the South Atlantic. The UK government has confirmed it will invest £180m over the next ten years to defend the Falklands, with an upgrade of a surface-to-air missile system and the deployment of two Chinook helicopters.

A video has emerged showing the brutal attack of a three-legged cat named Freeman, who was mauled to death by two savage dogs in Tarring, West Sussex. The 90-second attack was captured on CCTV by a neighbor, who passed the footage on to the cat's owner, Tracy Lynch. The attack happened in Terry Rickards' front garden while he was away last week. The two large dogs, possibly Dobermans, were running loose and dragged the terrified cat onto the neighbor's lawn before tearing into it. A woman is seen in the video calling over the dogs and then walking off, leaving the cat to die in agony. The attack is described as callous, and police are investigating.

A Chinese woman named Zhu Diandian has become an internet sensation after she began sharing photos and videos of her life with her pet pig, which she raises and cares for as if it were a dog or a cat. The pig, named "Five Flowers," now weighs 187 pounds and sleeps, eats, and even goes for walks with Ms. Zhu. She even dresses the pig in a green T-shirt and a body harness. Ms. Zhu's husband is reportedly supportive of her unusual pet, but their dog and rabbit appear to be a bit jealous. Despite the attention, Ms. Zhu says that her primary goal is to ensure the pig is happy and well-cared for.
